<DOC><DOCNO> AP890623-0094 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1105EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-PoliceDisciplined     06-23 0329</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Police Disciplined,0336</SECOND><HEAD>L.A. Police Chief Disciplines 38 Officers in Violent Drug Raid</HEAD><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Thirty-eight police officers are beingdisciplined and some could be fired after inner-city residents fileda civil rights lawsuit saying their homes were vandalized and theywere terrorized during a drug raid.   ``This is not something I do with any joy at all,'' Chief DarylGates said during a news conference Thursday. ``But clearly, thesituation got out of control. The officers were trying very hard todo the right thing _ to solve the gang problem, to solve thenarcotics trafficking problem. Unfortunately, while doing the rightthing, they were doing it in the wrong way.''   A drive-by shooting involving gang members prompted the raid by88 officers Aug. 1. Police officials later determined that duringthe raid, walls and plumbing fixtures in four homes were smashed andsome residents were beaten and humiliated.   Nine officers have been ordered to appear before department Boardof Rights tribunals and face firing or long suspensions from dutywithout pay, Gates said. Twenty-five others agreed to suspensions of22 days or less without pay.   Three other officers had letters of reprimand placed in theirfiles, and a captain has been reassigned to another job at a lowersalary, Gates said.   The 38 were charged with violations ranging from lying todepartment investigators to damaging personal property.   In addition, two officers also involved in the raids haveresigned, and another was fired for an unrelated rules violation,police officials said.   Police seized crack cocaine, marijuana and a sawed-off rifleduring the raid, Gates said. Of 32 people taken into custody, ninewere arrested.   The lawsuit, filed in federal court by some of the 32, allegesthey were forced to whistle the theme song from the old AndyGriffith television show and run a gantlet of officers at the policestation. It also says that officers spray-painted walls of the homeswith such anti-gang slogans.</TEXT></DOC>